The paper deals with motion planning, which is a subfield of robotics (cs.RO). The use of graphs and trees in the proposed algorithms suggests that the paper may also belong to the computational geometry (cs.CG) subcategory. The paper also deals with collision checking and trajectory planning, which are common topics in control systems (cs.SY). The use of sampling-based algorithms and optimization techniques suggests that the paper may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) subcategory. Finally, the paper presents numerical examples, which suggests that it may also belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) subcategory.
